#:pack{:created-at #inst "2026-04-17T04:59:55.598-00:00",
       :version "2026.04",
       :rules
       [#:rule{:title "Clojure Polylith + per-file stratified design",
               :agent-behavior
               "- **Exception**: Pure interface files (pass-throughs only) are not bound by the 3-layer maximum\n   - However, if an interface has >5 layers, consider if the component should be split into smaller components",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message
                "Standard: Clojure Polylith + per-file stratified design"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:review :implement},
                :file-globs
                ["components/**/src/**/*.clj"
                 "components/**/src/**/*.cljc"
                 "bases/**/src/**/*.clj"
                 "bases/**/src/**/*.cljc"
                 "projects/**/src/**/*.clj"
                 "projects/**/src/**/*.cljc"]},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Clojure style guidelines\n\n## Polylith architecture (ALWAYS)\n\n- Workspace: `components/`, `bases/`, `projects/`.\n\n- **Cross-component deps** must target `...<component>.interface` (not `.core`).\n- `bases` can depend on component **interfaces**; `projects` can depend on bases and component interfaces.\n- `components` may depend on other components **only via** their `.interface` ns.\n- **Never** depend on `projects` from `bases` or `components`.\n\n## Polylith stability tagging (ALWAYS)\n\n- Create stable tags **only after verification** (E2E tests + dogfooding runs), **not on every merge**.\n- Tag format: `git tag -a stable-YYYYMMDD -m \"Stable: <milestone description>\"`\n- Stable tags tell `poly info` which components have changed since last verified state.\n- Without stable tags, `poly info` shows all components as changed (since initial commit).\n- See **N1-architecture.md § 4.2.2** for complete tagging guidelines and verification checklist.\n\n## Per-file stratified design (ALWAYS)\n\n- Structure each ns with **labeled strata** as headings:\n\n  - `;------------------------------------------------------------------------------ Layer 0`\n  - `;------------------------------------------------------------------------------ Layer 1`\n  - …\n- **Reverse DAG**: Layer 0 at the top (pure/value-level); higher layers may call lower ones but not vice-versa.\n- **Max 3 strata** per file. If you need more, split the namespace.\n- Reserve the **very bottom** of the file for a `(comment …)` section (REPL testing). No `def/defn/defmacro` after it.\n\n## Component layout conventions\n\n### Required structure\n\n- `components/<name>/src/.../<name>/interface.clj` — **Complete public API surface**\n- `components/<name>/src/.../<name>/core.clj` — Main implementation (≤ 3 layers)\n- `components/<name>/src/.../<name>/spec.clj` — Malli schemas only; no functions except inside `(comment ...)`\n\n### Interface.clj pattern (CRITICAL)\n\n**Layer guidance for interfaces:**\n\n- The 3-layer maximum is **not a hard rule** for pure interface files that only contain pass-through functions\n- However, if an interface has many layers (>5), it may indicate the component is doing too much\n- Consider splitting large components into smaller, focused components to maintain simplicity and clear boundaries\n- Example: An agent component with 10 layers of pass-throughs might be better as separate planner,<br>\nimplementer, and tester components\n\n**Interface requirements:**\n\n- **interface.clj must contain ALL public functions** for the component\n- **interface.clj should contain NO implementations** — only thin pass-throughs\n- Pass-through functions forward to implementation functions in `core.clj` or other namespaces within the component\n- Input validation (specs) should happen in interface before forwarding\n- Example:\n\n  ```clojure\n  ;; CORRECT: interface.clj\n  (defn create-task\n    \"Create a new task (public API).\"\n    [task-data]\n    (s/validate ::task-spec task-data)\n    (core/create-task-impl task-data))\n\n  ;; WRONG: implementation in interface\n  (defn create-task [task-data]\n    (let [id (uuid/v4)\n          task (assoc task-data :id id)]\n      (store/save! task)))\n  ```\n\n### Implementation organization\n\n- **core.clj** — Main implementation logic; organized in ≤ 3 layers\n- **Additional namespaces** — When core.clj exceeds 3 layers or becomes too large:\n  - **Related functions** → subnamespaces (e.g., `views/table.clj`, `views/chart.clj`, `views/panel.clj`)\n  - **Unrelated functions** → separate namespaces (e.g., `executor.clj`, `factory.clj`, `validator.clj`)\n- **Protocol files** — `protocol.clj` for defining protocols/interfaces\n- All implementation namespaces are internal to the component; only `interface.clj` is public\n\n### Namespace splitting strategy\n\nWhen a file exceeds 3 layers:\n\n1. **Identify coherent groups** of functions\n2. **For related functions** (e.g., different views, different formatters):\n   - Create subnamespace: `components/<name>/src/.../<name>/<group>/<subname>.clj`\n   - Example: `reporting/views/table.clj`, `reporting/views/chart.clj`\n3. **For unrelated functions** (e.g., executor + factory + validator):\n   - Create separate namespaces: `components/<name>/src/.../<name>/<concern>.clj`\n   - Example: `agent/executor.clj`, `agent/factory.clj`, `agent/memory.clj`\n4. **Update interface.clj** to import and forward to new namespaces\n5. **Keep each new file** to ≤ 3 layers\n\n## Map access patterns (ALWAYS)\n\n- **Prefer `(get m k default)` over `(or (:k m) default)`**\n\n  ```clojure\n  ;; BAD — silently returns default for any falsy value (false, 0, \"\")\n  (or (:timeout opts) 5000)\n\n  ;; GOOD — explicit default, survives falsy values\n  (get opts :timeout 5000)\n  ```\n\n- The `(or (:k m) fallback)` form is only acceptable when choosing between two\n  **different keys** in the same map (canonical vs. legacy field), never when\n  `fallback` is a computed or literal default:\n\n  ```clojure\n  ;; Acceptable — picking between two key names for the same semantic field\n  (or (get event :workflow/id) (get event :workflow-id))\n\n  ;; BAD — use get with default instead\n  (or (:workflow/id event) \"unknown\")          ; → (get event :workflow/id \"unknown\")\n  (or (:tokens result) total-tokens)           ; → (get result :tokens total-tokens)\n  ```\n\n## Anonymous functions (ALWAYS)\n\nAnonymous functions (`fn` / `#(...)`) should be used **only when they enhance\nthe clarity of the surrounding code** — not as a default for every callback.\n\n**Prefer named functions when:**\n\n- The logic has a name worth expressing (extract to `defn-`)\n- The body is more than one non-trivial expression\n- The function is used more than once\n- The parent expression already reads at a high level of abstraction and the\n  anonymous body forces the reader to shift mental levels mid-expression\n\n**Acceptable anonymous function uses:**\n\n```clojure\n;; Short, self-evident predicate inline — intent is clear from context\n(filter :active? users)\n(remove nil? results)\n(keep :name items)\n\n;; Simple structural transform that names itself through context\n(map #(assoc % :processed? true) records)\n\n;; One-off adaptor that has no reusable name\n(sort-by #(get key->cat %) rule-ids)\n```\n\n**Extract to a named function when the body obscures intent:**\n\n```clojure\n;; BAD — the anon fn body is complex and the parent reads poorly\n(into {} (map (fn [[k vs]]\n                [k (get (first vs) :rule/category \"0\")])\n              groups))\n\n;; GOOD — named fn expresses the intent; parent reads as a pipeline\n(defn- key->category-entry [[k vs]]\n  [k (get (first vs) :rule/category \"0\")])\n\n(into {} (map key->category-entry groups))\n```\n\n**Never embed anonymous functions in data maps as configuration values.**\nConfiguration maps should reference named functions so the config remains\ndata and the behavior is separately testable:\n\n```clojure\n;; BAD — anonymous fn buried in a map; untestable, hard to read\n{:file-pred (fn [path] (str/ends-with? path \".clj\"))}\n\n;; GOOD — named fn at the correct stratum; referenced by the config\n(defn- clojure-file? [path] (str/ends-with? path \".clj\"))\n\n{:file-pred clojure-file?}\n```\n\n## Agent behavior\n\nWhen creating/editing a namespace:\n\n1) Insert/maintain **Layer 0/1/2** headings and keep them **monotonic increasing** (0 → 1 → 2).\n2) Keep **pure helpers** and external calls that are side-effect free in **Layer 0**.\n3) Put orchestration that **only depends on Layer 0** in **Layer 1**, and so on.\n4) If you cross 3 layers, **propose a split** using the namespace splitting strategy above.\n   - **Exception**: Pure interface files (pass-throughs only) are not bound by the 3-layer maximum\n   - However, if an interface has >5 layers, consider if the component should be split into smaller components\n5) Ensure the last top-level form is a single `(comment …)` block with quick REPL samples.\n6) For cross-component calls, target `...<other>.interface` — and surface a fix if `.core` is used.\n\n## Examples\n\n### Good: Thin interface with pass-through\n\n```clojure\n;; components/task/src/ai/miniforge/task/interface.clj\n(ns ai.miniforge.task.interface\n  (:require [ai.miniforge.task.core :as core]\n            [ai.miniforge.task.validator :as validator]))\n\n;------------------------------------------------------------------------------ Layer 0\n;; Public API - validation + forwarding only\n\n(defn create-task\n  \"Create a new task.\"\n  [task-data]\n  (validator/validate-task-data task-data)\n  (core/create-task-impl task-data))\n\n(defn get-task\n  \"Retrieve task by ID.\"\n  [task-id]\n  (core/get-task-impl task-id))\n```\n\n### Good: Split oversized file by related functions\n\n```clojure\n;; Before: reporting/views.clj with 8 layers\n;; After:\n;; - reporting/views/table.clj (≤3 layers)\n;; - reporting/views/chart.clj (≤3 layers)\n;; - reporting/views/panel.clj (≤3 layers)\n\n;; components/reporting/src/ai/miniforge/reporting/interface.clj\n(ns ai.miniforge.reporting.interface\n  (:require [ai.miniforge.reporting.views.table :as table]\n            [ai.miniforge.reporting.views.chart :as chart]\n            [ai.miniforge.reporting.views.panel :as panel]))\n\n(defn render-table [data] (table/render data))\n(defn render-chart [data] (chart/render data))\n(defn render-panel [data] (panel/render data))\n```\n\n### Bad: Implementation in interface\n\n```clojure\n;; components/task/src/ai/miniforge/task/interface.clj\n(ns ai.miniforge.task.interface\n  (:require [datalevin.core :as d]))\n\n;; WRONG: Implementation details in interface\n(defn create-task [task-data]\n  (let [conn (d/get-conn)\n        id (java.util.UUID/randomUUID)\n        task (assoc task-data :id id :created-at (java.time.Instant/now))]\n    (d/transact! conn [task])\n    task))\n```",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/clojure,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "210",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (210): Clojure Polylith + per-file stratified design"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Code quality — composable pipelines, no nested conditionals, DRY component extraction",
               :agent-behavior
               "When writing or reviewing code:\n1. If a function exceeds one screen, ask: can this be split into named pipeline stages?\n2. If you see nested `if`/`when` blocks, refactor to `cond` or guard clauses.\n3. If you find yourself duplicating a function from another namespace, stop — create or identify the right component and add it to the interface.\n4. Composition is the design. Don't name composed pipelines \"main\" or \"run\" — name them for what they produce.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message
                "Standard: Code quality — composable pipelines, no nested conditionals, DRY component extraction"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement}},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Code Quality (ALWAYS)\n\n## Composable functions — small and pipeline-oriented\n\nEvery function must read as a **pipeline**: data enters, transforms, exits. No hidden branches, no side effects buried in the middle, no implicit state mutations.\n\n**Design rule:** Write the smallest function that does one thing. Compose up.\n\n```clojure\n;; BAD — one function does discovery, filtering, and formatting\n(defn process-results [items]\n  (let [results []]\n    (doseq [item items]\n      (when (valid? item)\n        (when-let [x (transform item)]\n          (conj results (format x)))))\n    results))\n\n;; GOOD — three pure functions, each one concern\n(defn valid-items   [items]   (filter valid? items))\n(defn transform-all [items]   (keep transform items))\n(defn format-all    [items]   (mapv format items))\n\n;; Composed pipeline — reads as data flow\n(defn process-results [items]\n  (-> items valid-items transform-all format-all))\n```\n\nThe composed form is **the function** — not a \"main\" that calls helpers. There is no incidental complexity.\n\n## No nested conditionals\n\nNested `if`/`cond`/`when` blocks are a signal that control flow and data transformation are entangled. Restructure instead.\n\n**Prefer:**\n- Guard clauses (`when`/`if` at the top, return early via `nil` or exception)\n- `cond->` / `cond->>` for conditional transformation chains\n- Lookup tables / dispatch maps over `cond` branches\n- `some->` / `some->>` for optional-chain patterns\n\n```clojure\n;; BAD — nested conditionals\n(defn classify [evt]\n  (if (= :workflow/started (:event/type evt))\n    (if-let [id (:workflow/id evt)]\n      (if (valid-id? id)\n        :valid-start\n        :bad-id)\n      :missing-id)\n    :not-a-start))\n\n;; GOOD — flat cond\n(defn classify [evt]\n  (let [type (:event/type evt)\n        id   (:workflow/id evt)]\n    (cond\n      (not= :workflow/started type) :not-a-start\n      (nil? id)                     :missing-id\n      (not (valid-id? id))          :bad-id\n      :else                         :valid-start)))\n```\n\nA maximum of **one level of conditional nesting** is the goal. Two levels demands a refactor. Three is never acceptable.\n\n## DRY — extract to a component, import the interface\n\nDuplication of logic is a signal that a component boundary is missing.\n\n**Rules:**\n- If two components share more than one helper function, that logic belongs in a third component.\n- Never copy-paste implementations across namespaces. If you find yourself doing so, stop and create a shared component.\n- The shared component exposes an `interface.clj`. Consumers depend on the interface, never on the internal namespace.\n\n```\n;; BAD: same timestamp normalization in events.clj and workflows.clj\n(defn normalize-ts [ts] ...)  ; duplicated!\n\n;; GOOD: shared component\ncomponents/temporal/src/ai/miniforge/temporal/interface.clj\n  (def normalize-ts core/normalize-ts)\n\n;; Consumers:\n(:require [ai.miniforge.temporal.interface :as temporal])\n(temporal/normalize-ts ts)\n```\n\n**What belongs in a component:**\n- Any pure function used in more than one component\n- Any protocol/schema referenced across components\n- Any formatting or parsing utility with multiple callers\n\n**What stays local:**\n- Functions called only within one component's internal namespaces\n\n## Agent behavior\n\nWhen writing or reviewing code:\n1. If a function exceeds one screen, ask: can this be split into named pipeline stages?\n2. If you see nested `if`/`when` blocks, refactor to `cond` or guard clauses.\n3. If you find yourself duplicating a function from another namespace, stop — create or identify the right component and add it to the interface.\n4. Composition is the design. Don't name composed pipelines \"main\" or \"run\" — name them for what they produce.\n\n## Anti-patterns to reject\n\n- Functions with multiple concerns named after a verb (e.g., `process-and-save`, `load-and-validate`)\n- `let` bindings that grow to 10+ forms — split the function\n- `cond` branches with `let` bodies — extract each branch to a named function\n- Utility functions copied between components instead of extracted\n- \"Helper\" files that grow without bound because no component owns them",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/code-quality,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "002",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (002): Code quality — composable pipelines, no nested conditionals, DRY component extraction"}
        #:rule{:title "DateVer versioning convention",
               :agent-behavior
               "- When generating versions, use `(version)` from build.clj\n- Never use SemVer (X.Y.Z) format\n- In changelogs, use DateVer headings: `## 2026.01.18.1`",
               :enforcement
               {:action :audit,
                :message "Standard: DateVer versioning convention"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement},
                :file-globs
                ["build.clj"
                 "**/version.edn"
                 ".github/workflows/*.yml"]},
               :severity :minor,
               :knowledge-content
               "# DateVer Versioning (ALWAYS)\n\nUse **DateVer** instead of SemVer for all version numbers.\n\n## Format\n\n```zsh\nYYYY.MM.DD.N\n```\n\nWhere:\n\n- `YYYY` — four-digit year\n- `MM` — two-digit month (zero-padded)\n- `DD` — two-digit day (zero-padded)\n- `N` — build number for the day (1-indexed)\n\n## Examples\n\n| Version | Meaning |\n|---------|---------|\n| `2026.01.18.1` | First build on January 18, 2026 |\n| `2026.01.18.5` | Fifth build on January 18, 2026 |\n| `2026.03.01.1` | First build on March 1, 2026 |\n\n## Rationale\n\n- **Chronologically sortable**: Versions naturally sort by time\n- **No arbitrary major/minor**: Avoids bikeshedding about \"breaking changes\"\n- **Self-documenting**: Version tells you when it was built\n- **Simple**: One rule—today's date plus build count\n\n## Implementation\n\n```clojure\n;; In build.clj\n(defn version []\n  (let [now   (java.time.LocalDate/now)\n        year  (.getYear now)\n        month (.getMonthValue now)\n        day   (.getDayOfMonth now)\n        n     (today-commit-count)]\n    (format \"%d.%02d.%02d.%d\" year month day n)))\n```\n\n## Git Tags\n\nTag releases as `v{version}`:\n\n```bash\ngit tag v2026.01.18.1\ngit push origin v2026.01.18.1\n```\n\n## Comparison to SemVer\n\n| SemVer | DateVer | Notes |\n|--------|---------|-------|\n| 1.0.0 | 2026.01.15.1 | Initial release |\n| 1.0.1 | 2026.01.15.2 | Bug fix same day |\n| 1.1.0 | 2026.01.20.1 | Feature add |\n| 2.0.0 | 2026.03.01.1 | \"Breaking change\" (no special handling) |\n\nBreaking changes are communicated via changelog and documentation, not version numbers.\n\n## Agent Behavior\n\n- When generating versions, use `(version)` from build.clj\n- Never use SemVer (X.Y.Z) format\n- In changelogs, use DateVer headings: `## 2026.01.18.1`",
               :id :std/datever,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "730",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (730): DateVer versioning convention"}
        #:rule{:title "Git branch management",
               :agent-behavior
               "**CRITICAL**: **ALWAYS create a new session unique git worktree for your session.\n**CRITICAL**: **ALWAYS create new branches from `main` or `master` (the primary branch) unless explicitly requested otherwise.**",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message "Standard: Git branch management"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement}},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Git Branch & PR Management (ALWAYS)\n\n## Branch Creation Rules\n\n**CRITICAL**: **ALWAYS create a new session unique git worktree for your session.\n**CRITICAL**: **ALWAYS create new branches from `main` or `master` (the primary branch) unless explicitly requested otherwise.**\n\n### Pre-Branch Checklist\n\nBefore running `git checkout -b <new-branch>`:\n\n1. **ALWAYS** checkout the primary branch first: `git checkout main` (or `master`)\n2. **ALWAYS** pull latest changes: `git pull origin main` (or `master`)\n3. **VERIFY** you're on the primary branch: `git branch --show-current`\n4. **VERIFY** branch is clean: `git status` (should show \"nothing to commit\")\n5. **ONLY THEN** create the new branch: `git checkout -b <new-branch>`\n\n**Never assume you're on main - always explicitly checkout main first.**\n\n### Never Branch from Feature Branches\n\n❌ **BAD**: Creating a feature branch from another feature branch\n\n```bash\n# On migrate/feature-a\ngit checkout -b migrate/feature-b  # ❌ Wrong - carries feature-a changes\n```\n\n✅ **GOOD**: Always branch from main\n\n```bash\ngit checkout main           # ALWAYS do this first\ngit pull origin main        # ALWAYS pull latest\ngit checkout -b migrate/feature-b  # ✅ Correct - clean start\n```\n\n### Exception: Dependent PRs\n\n**Only branch from another feature branch when:**\n\n1. User **explicitly** requests: \"create this branch from <branch-name>\"\n2. User **explicitly** confirms: \"yes, branch from that branch\"\n3. There's a documented dependency chain that requires it\n4. The dependency is clearly stated in the PR description\n\n**Default behavior**: Always branch from main unless user explicitly says otherwise.\n\n## PR Scope Rules\n\n### Single Purpose PRs\n\nEach PR should have **one focused purpose**:\n\n- ✅ Migrate security groups batch 1\n- ✅ Migrate IAM policies for ElasticSearch\n- ❌ Migrate security groups + DynamoDB + IAM roles (mixed concerns)\n\n### Verify PR Contents Before Pushing\n\nBefore pushing a branch, run:\n\n```bash\ngit log origin/main..HEAD --oneline\ngit diff origin/main..HEAD --stat\n```\n\nThis shows what will be in the PR to catch unintended changes.\n\n## Agent Behavior (Cursor)\n\n### Before Creating Any Branch\n\n1. **ALWAYS** checkout main first: `git checkout main` (or `master`)\n2. **ALWAYS** pull latest: `git pull origin main` (or `master`)\n3. **VERIFY** you're on main: `git branch --show-current`\n4. **VERIFY** branch is clean: `git status`\n5. **ONLY THEN** create new branch: `git checkout -b <new-feature-branch>`\n\n**Never create a branch without first explicitly checking out main.**\n\n### Before Pushing a Branch\n\n1. Run `git log origin/main..HEAD --oneline` \n2. Verify commits match the intended PR scope\n3. If unintended changes detected:\n   - Alert the user\n   - Offer to recreate the branch cleanly from main\n   - Do NOT push the contaminated branch\n\n### PR Documentation\n\nIn PR docs, include:\n\n- **Base Branch**: State whether based on `main` or another feature branch\n- **Depends On**: List any prerequisite PRs that must merge first\n\n## Common Mistakes to Avoid\n\n1. **Branching from wrong branch** - Always verify with `git branch` first\n2. **Stale main** - Pull latest main before branching\n3. **Mixed PR scope** - If unrelated changes appear, recreate branch from main\n4. **Dependent branches without documentation** - Make dependencies explicit\n\n## When in Doubt\n\n- Check git state first\n- Create a unique git worktree for your work\n- Branch from main\n- Keep PRs focused and single-purpose",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/git-branch-management,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "710",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (710): Git branch management"}
        #:rule{:title "Git Worktrees",
               :agent-behavior
               "Git worktrees enable multiple branches to be checked out simultaneously in separate directories from a single repository.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :audit, :message "Standard: Git Worktrees"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement}},
               :severity :minor,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Git Worktrees for Parallel Workflows\n\n## Context\n\nGit worktrees enable multiple branches to be checked out simultaneously in separate directories from a single repository.\n\n**Core Principle: AI agents always work in their own dedicated worktree.** This ensures isolation, prevents conflicts, and enables concurrent operations.\n\nThe following types of worktrees support different use cases:\n\n1. **AI session isolation**: Each AI agent session operates in its own worktree to prevent conflicts\n2. **Development workflow**: Working on multiple features without branch switching overhead\n3. **miniforge architecture**: The Operator agent managing multiple concurrent workflows with isolated contexts\n4. **IDE integration**: Dedicated worktrees for different editors (e.g., Cursor on `main` for stable reference)\n\n## Development Usage\n\n### Creating Worktrees\n\n**For feature work:**\n```bash\n# Create new worktree with new branch\ngit worktree add -b feat/new-feature /path/to/worktree origin/main\n\n# Example: artifact component\ngit worktree add -b feat/artifact-component \\\n  <repo>/ \\\n  origin/main\n```\n\n**For IDE isolation:**\n```bash\n# Permanent worktree for Cursor IDE (stays on main)\ngit worktree add <repo>/ main\n```\n\n### Standard Worktree Layout\n\n```\nminiforge.ai/\n├── miniforge/                  # Main worktree (for active feature work)\n├── miniforge-cursor/           # Permanent: Cursor IDE on main branch\n├── miniforge-claude-*/         # AI Session: Claude Code session worktrees (clean up before new session)\n├── miniforge-cursor-ai-*/      # AI Session: Cursor AI session worktrees (clean up before new session)\n├── miniforge-{feature}/        # Temporary: One per active feature PR\n└── miniforge-{context}/        # Optional: For operator spawned workflows\n```\n\n### Worktree Lifecycle\n\n**1. Create** (when starting feature):\n```bash\ngit worktree add -b feat/component-name /path/to/miniforge-component origin/main\n```\n\n**2. Work** (develop in isolation):\n```bash\ncd /path/to/miniforge-component\n# All git operations work normally\ngit add, commit, push, etc.\n```\n\n**3. Cleanup** (after PR merge):\n```bash\n# Remove the worktree directory\ngit worktree remove /path/to/miniforge-component\n\n# Delete remote branch (if not auto-deleted)\ngit push origin --delete feat/component-name\n\n# Prune stale references\ngit worktree prune\ngit fetch --prune\n```\n\n### Cleanup Checklist\n\n**After every PR merge**, clean up:\n\n- [ ] `git worktree remove /path/to/feature-worktree`\n- [ ] `git push origin --delete feat/branch-name` (if needed)\n- [ ] `git fetch --prune` (update local refs)\n- [ ] Verify: `git worktree list` shows only active worktrees\n\n**Before starting each new AI session**, clean up:\n\n- [ ] Remove old AI session worktrees (see \"AI Session Lifecycle Management\" below)\n- [ ] `git worktree prune` - Clean up stale references\n- [ ] Verify: No stale `miniforge-claude-*` or `miniforge-cursor-ai-*` worktrees remain\n\n### Worktree Types and Lifecycle\n\n**AI Session Worktrees** (delete when starting new session):\n- `miniforge-claude-*` - Claude Code AI session worktrees\n- `miniforge-cursor-ai-*` - Cursor AI session worktrees\n- Created automatically or manually for each AI agent session\n- **MUST be cleaned up** when starting a new AI session to prevent stale state\n- Naming convention: `miniforge-{ai-tool}-{date}` or `miniforge-{ai-tool}-{session-id}`\n\n**Permanent** (keep indefinitely):\n- `miniforge-cursor` - Dedicated IDE worktree on `main`\n- `miniforge` - Main development worktree (reuse by switching branches)\n\n**Temporary** (delete after merge):\n- `miniforge-{feature}` - Created per feature, removed after PR merge\n- `miniforge-{fix}` - Created for urgent fixes, removed after merge\n\n### AI Session Lifecycle Management\n\n**CRITICAL: Always clean up old AI session worktrees before starting a new session.**\n\n#### Starting a New AI Session\n\n**1. Check for existing AI session worktrees:**\n```bash\ngit worktree list | grep -E 'miniforge-(claude|cursor-ai)'\n```\n\n**2. Remove old AI session worktrees:**\n```bash\n# Remove each old session worktree\ngit worktree remove /path/to/miniforge-claude-old-session\n\n# If worktree was manually deleted, prune stale references\ngit worktree prune\n```\n\n**3. Clean up associated branches (if any):**\n```bash\n# List AI session branches\ngit branch | grep -E 'claude-session|ai-session'\n\n# Delete local branches that are no longer needed\ngit branch -D branch-name\n\n# Delete remote branches if pushed\ngit push origin --delete branch-name\n```\n\n**4. Create new session worktree:**\n```bash\n# Option A: Work on existing branch\ngit worktree add -b feat/my-feature \\\n  <repo>/ +%Y%m%d) \\\n  origin/main\n\n# Option B: Continue work on existing feature branch\ngit worktree add \\\n  <repo>/ +%Y%m%d) \\\n  feat/existing-feature\n```\n\n#### Session Cleanup Checklist\n\nBefore starting each new AI session:\n\n- [ ] `git worktree list` - List all worktrees\n- [ ] Identify old AI session worktrees (`miniforge-claude-*`, `miniforge-cursor-ai-*`)\n- [ ] `git worktree remove /path/to/old-session` - Remove each old session\n- [ ] `git worktree prune` - Clean up stale references\n- [ ] `git branch -D` - Delete local session branches if no longer needed\n- [ ] `git push origin --delete` - Delete remote session branches if pushed\n- [ ] Verify: Only current/active worktrees remain\n\n#### Why Session Cleanup Matters\n\n**Prevents stale state:**\n- Old session worktrees may have uncommitted changes or conflicts\n- Branch state diverges from remote over time\n- Disk space accumulates with multiple abandoned sessions\n\n**Ensures clean context:**\n- Each AI session starts from a known state\n- No confusion about which worktree is active\n- Clear separation between different work streams\n\n**Best practice:**\n- **Always create a fresh worktree** for each new AI session\n- **Never reuse** old session worktrees across different sessions\n- **Commit or stash** work before ending a session if you want to preserve it\n\n## miniforge Operator Usage\n\n### Architectural Significance\n\nGit worktrees are a **native feature** for miniforge's multi-loop architecture:\n\n```\nOperator Agent\n    ├── Main Workflow     → miniforge/           (feat/user-feature)\n    ├── Fix Workflow      → miniforge-fix-123/   (fix/workflow-error)\n    ├── Test Workflow     → miniforge-test-456/  (test/new-strategy)\n    └── Review Context    → miniforge-cursor/    (main, read-only)\n```\n\n**Benefits for Operator:**\n\n1. **Isolation**: Each workflow has its own working directory\n   - No branch switching conflicts\n   - Independent git state per workflow\n   - Clean context separation\n\n2. **Concurrency**: Multiple workflows run in parallel\n   - Main feature continues while fix is being developed\n   - Test strategies can run without blocking main work\n   - No mutex on repository access\n\n3. **Provenance**: Each worktree maps to a workflow instance\n   - Clear artifact → worktree → branch mapping\n   - Easy debugging (inspect worktree state)\n   - Audit trail via git history per worktree\n\n4. **Recovery**: Pause/resume workflows naturally\n   - Worktree persists if workflow paused\n   - Resume by switching to worktree directory\n   - Crash recovery: worktree state is on disk\n\n### Operator Workflow Pattern\n\n```clojure\n;; Operator spawns fix workflow\n(defn spawn-fix-workflow [operator problem]\n  (let [worktree-path (str \"/tmp/miniforge-fix-\" (uuid))\n        branch-name (str \"fix/\" (kebab-case (:description problem)))]\n\n    ;; Create isolated worktree\n    (shell \"git\" \"worktree\" \"add\" \"-b\" branch-name worktree-path \"origin/main\")\n\n    ;; Start workflow in worktree context\n    (start-workflow {:type :fix\n                     :context {:cwd worktree-path\n                               :branch branch-name}\n                     :problem problem})\n\n    ;; Cleanup after merge\n    (on-workflow-complete\n      (fn [result]\n        (shell \"git\" \"worktree\" \"remove\" worktree-path)\n        (shell \"git\" \"push\" \"origin\" \"--delete\" branch-name)))))\n```\n\n### Worktree Metadata for Workflows\n\nTrack worktrees in operator state:\n\n```clojure\n{:workflows\n [{:id #uuid \"...\"\n   :type :main\n   :worktree \"<repo>/"\n   :branch \"feat/user-feature\"\n   :status :running}\n\n  {:id #uuid \"...\"\n   :type :fix\n   :worktree \"/tmp/miniforge-fix-abc123\"\n   :branch \"fix/validation-error\"\n   :status :running\n   :spawned-by #uuid \"...\"}  ; parent workflow\n\n  {:id #uuid \"...\"\n   :type :review\n   :worktree \"<repo>/"\n   :branch \"main\"\n   :status :read-only}]}\n```\n\n## Common Patterns\n\n### Pattern: Feature Development\n```bash\n# Start feature\ngit worktree add -b feat/new-thing miniforge-new-thing origin/main\ncd miniforge-new-thing\n# ... develop ...\ngit push -u origin feat/new-thing\ngh pr create\n\n# After merge\ngit worktree remove miniforge-new-thing\ngit push origin --delete feat/new-thing\n```\n\n### Pattern: Urgent Fix While Feature in Progress\n```bash\n# Main feature work in progress at miniforge/\n# Spawn fix without disrupting main work\ngit worktree add -b fix/urgent-bug miniforge-urgent-fix origin/main\ncd miniforge-urgent-fix\n# ... fix bug ...\ngit push -u origin fix/urgent-bug\ngh pr create --base main\n\n# After merge, cleanup\ngit worktree remove miniforge-urgent-fix\n\n# Main feature work continues uninterrupted at miniforge/\n```\n\n### Pattern: Operator Self-Improvement\n```bash\n# Operator detects problem in its own workflow\n# Spawns fix workflow in isolated worktree\ngit worktree add -b fix/workflow-123 /tmp/miniforge-self-fix origin/main\n# Fix workflow runs independently\n# Main workflow continues or pauses\n# After fix merged, resume main workflow\ngit worktree remove /tmp/miniforge-self-fix\n```\n\n### Pattern: AI Session Workflow\n```bash\n# Before starting new AI session - clean up old sessions\ngit worktree list | grep miniforge-claude\n# Remove any old session worktrees found\ngit worktree remove /path/to/old/miniforge-claude-20260115\ngit worktree prune\n\n# Start new AI session with fresh worktree\ngit worktree add -b feat/new-feature \\\n  <repo>/ +%Y%m%d) \\\n  origin/main\n\n# AI agent works in isolated session worktree\ncd <repo>/ ... AI agent makes changes, commits, creates PR ...\n\n# After PR merged OR before next session\ngit worktree remove <repo>/ push origin --delete feat/new-feature  # if needed\n```\n\n### Pattern: Resuming Work Across AI Sessions\n```bash\n# Session 1: Start work on feature\ngit worktree add -b feat/my-feature \\\n  miniforge-claude-session1 \\\n  origin/main\n# ... work in progress, committed to branch ...\n\n# End Session 1 (commit/push work first!)\ngit -C miniforge-claude-session1 push -u origin feat/my-feature\ngit worktree remove miniforge-claude-session1\n\n# Session 2: Resume work on same feature in NEW worktree\ngit worktree add \\\n  miniforge-claude-session2 \\\n  feat/my-feature  # checkout existing branch\n# ... continue work ...\n\n# Always use fresh worktree, never reuse old session directory\n```\n\n## Anti-Patterns\n\n❌ **Don't**: Check out `main` in multiple worktrees\n```bash\n# BAD: Will fail\ngit worktree add miniforge-feature main  # Error: main already checked out\n```\n\n✅ **Do**: Create feature branches\n```bash\n# GOOD: Each worktree has unique branch\ngit worktree add -b feat/feature miniforge-feature origin/main\n```\n\n❌ **Don't**: Leave worktrees after merge\n```bash\n# BAD: Accumulates stale worktrees\ngit worktree list\n# /path/to/merged-feature-1  (merged 3 months ago)\n# /path/to/merged-feature-2  (merged 2 months ago)\n```\n\n✅ **Do**: Clean up immediately after merge\n```bash\n# GOOD: Clean up as part of merge process\ngit worktree remove /path/to/feature\ngit push origin --delete feat/branch\n```\n\n❌ **Don't**: Use worktrees for long-lived branches\n```bash\n# BAD: Creates confusion\ngit worktree add miniforge-staging staging\ngit worktree add miniforge-production production\n```\n\n✅ **Do**: Use worktrees for isolated, temporary work\n```bash\n# GOOD: Short-lived feature branches\ngit worktree add -b feat/component miniforge-component origin/main\n```\n\n❌ **Don't**: Reuse old AI session worktrees across sessions\n```bash\n# BAD: Reusing old session worktree leads to stale state\n# Session 1 ended, but worktree still exists\ncd miniforge-claude-20260115  # From yesterday\n# Start new work here - BAD! May have uncommitted changes, stale branch state\n```\n\n✅ **Do**: Create fresh worktree for each AI session\n```bash\n# GOOD: Clean slate for each session\ngit worktree remove miniforge-claude-20260115  # Clean up old session\ngit worktree add -b feat/new miniforge-claude-$(date +%Y%m%d) origin/main\n```\n\n❌ **Don't**: Skip cleanup when starting new AI session\n```bash\n# BAD: Start new session without cleanup\ngit worktree add -b feat/new miniforge-claude-20260120 origin/main\n# Now you have multiple stale session worktrees cluttering your workspace\n```\n\n✅ **Do**: Always clean up before starting new session\n```bash\n# GOOD: Clean up first\ngit worktree list | grep miniforge-claude  # Check for old sessions\ngit worktree remove miniforge-claude-old   # Remove them\ngit worktree add -b feat/new miniforge-claude-$(date +%Y%m%d) origin/main\n```\n\n## Troubleshooting\n\n### Worktree already exists\n```bash\n# Error: 'feat/branch' is already checked out at '/path/to/worktree'\n# Fix: Remove old worktree first\ngit worktree remove /path/to/worktree\n# Or: Prune if directory was manually deleted\ngit worktree prune\n```\n\n### Can't delete worktree\n```bash\n# Error: working tree already exists\n# Fix: Make sure no processes are using the directory\nlsof +D /path/to/worktree  # Check open files\ngit worktree remove --force /path/to/worktree  # Force removal\n```\n\n### Branch deleted but worktree remains\n```bash\n# Clean up stale worktrees\ngit worktree prune\ngit fetch --prune\n```\n\n## Integration with miniforge\n\n### Phase 3: Control Plane Implementation\n\nWhen implementing the Operator agent:\n\n1. **Worktree Manager** component\n   - Create/remove worktrees per workflow\n   - Track worktree → workflow mapping\n   - Cleanup on workflow completion\n\n2. **Workflow Isolation**\n   - Each workflow runs in dedicated worktree\n   - File system isolation prevents conflicts\n   - Git state isolation prevents race conditions\n\n3. **Monitoring**\n   - `git worktree list` shows active workflows\n   - Disk usage monitoring per worktree\n   - Automatic cleanup of abandoned worktrees\n\n### Future: Distributed miniforge\n\nWorktrees enable **local multi-loop** execution. For distributed:\n- Each node creates local worktrees\n- Shared git remote coordinates state\n- Worktree per workflow instance per node\n\n## References\n\n- Git worktree docs: `git help worktree`\n- See also: [710-git-branch-management.mdc](./710-git-branch-management.mdc)\n- See also: [721-pr-documentation.mdc](./721-pr-documentation.mdc)\n- Architecture: `docs/specs/operational-modes.spec` (Operator agent)\n\n---\n\n**Rule**: AI agents always work in their own dedicated worktree. Use git worktrees for AI session isolation, parallel development, and operator multi-loop execution. Always clean up old AI session worktrees before starting a new session. Create worktrees per feature, cleanup after merge. Leverage for miniforge's concurrent workflow architecture.",
               :id :std/git-worktrees,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "725",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (725): Git Worktrees"}
