        #:rule{:title
               "Result handling — use success?/failed? predicates and success/anomaly constructors",
               :agent-behavior
               "When writing code that returns a result: 1. Use `schema/success` or `schema/failure` — never `{:success? true ...}`. 2. When checking a result from a called function, use `schema/succeeded?` or `schema/failed?` — never `:success?` key access. 3. If the result type comes from a different component, check what predicates that component's interface exports. If none exist, that's a gap to flag. 4.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message
                "Standard: Result handling — use success?/failed? predicates and success/anomaly constructors"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement}},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Result Handling (ALWAYS)\n\nOperations that can fail return a **result map**. Always use the provided predicates and constructors — never build result maps by hand or reach into their structure directly.\n\n## Predicates over structure inspection\n\n**Never** examine the shape of a result to determine success or failure. Use the predicates.\n\n```clojure\n;; BAD — reaching into the result map's internals\n(if (:success? result)\n  ...)\n\n(when (= :ok (:status result))\n  ...)\n\n(when (nil? (:error result))\n  ...)\n\n;; GOOD — use predicates\n(if (schema/succeeded? result)\n  ...)\n\n(when (schema/succeeded? result)\n  ...)\n```\n\nThe internal shape of a result map is an **implementation detail**. Code that depends on `:success?` being a boolean key breaks when the result format evolves. Predicates are the stable API.\n\n## Constructors over hand-built maps\n\n**Never** construct result maps with `{:success? true ...}` or `{:status :error ...}` literals. Use the provided constructors.\n\n```clojure\n;; BAD — hand-building result maps\n{:success? true  :data value  :errors nil}\n{:success? false :error \"Something went wrong\"}\n{:success? false :errors [{:msg \"invalid\"}]}\n\n;; GOOD — use schema constructors\n(schema/success :data value {:errors nil})\n(schema/failure :data error-message)\n(schema/failure-with-errors :data [{:msg \"invalid\"}])\n```\n\nConstructors enforce the canonical shape. They are also self-documenting: `(schema/failure-with-errors :pack errors)` communicates intent; `{:success? false :pack nil :errors errors}` does not.\n\n## Propagation — thread results through, don't unwrap\n\nWhen passing a result to a caller, propagate the result map — don't unwrap it and re-wrap it.\n\n```clojure\n;; BAD — unwrapping and re-wrapping\n(let [{:keys [success? data error]} (load-pack path)]\n  (if success?\n    {:ok true :pack data}\n    {:ok false :msg error}))\n\n;; GOOD — propagate\n(let [result (load-pack path)]\n  (if (schema/succeeded? result)\n    (process (:pack result))\n    result))  ; return the failure as-is for the caller\n```\n\n## What counts as an \"anomaly\"\n\nUse anomaly constructors (failure forms) for:\n- Validation failures (invalid input at a boundary)\n- Missing required resources (file not found, entity not found)\n- Downstream errors caught at a boundary\n\nDo NOT wrap expected nil return values as anomalies. A function that legitimately returns nil for \"not found\" is not failing — it's answering the question.\n\n## Agent behavior\n\nWhen writing code that returns a result:\n1. Use `schema/success` or `schema/failure` — never `{:success? true ...}`.\n2. When checking a result from a called function, use `schema/succeeded?` or `schema/failed?` — never `:success?` key access.\n3. If the result type comes from a different component, check what predicates that component's interface exports. If none exist, that's a gap to flag.\n4. When propagating failures up the call stack, return the result map unchanged — don't add new keys or translate the error.\n\n## Anti-patterns to reject\n\n- `(when (:success? result) ...)` — use predicate\n- `(assoc result :success? false)` — use constructor\n- `(if (nil? (:error result)) ...)` — use predicate\n- `(not (:failed? result))` — use `(succeeded? result)`\n- Mixing result-map checks with exception handling in the same function — separate concerns",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/result-handling,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "003",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (003): Result handling — use success?/failed? predicates and success/anomaly constructors"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Use ALWAYS when asked to CREATE A RULE or UPDATE A RULE or taught a lesson from the user that should be retained as a new rule for Cursor",
               :agent-behavior
               "```mdc\n---\ndewey: \"NNN\"\ndescription: ACTION when TRIGGER to OUTCOME\nglobs: *.mdc\n---",
               :enforcement
               {:action :audit,
                :message
                "Standard: Use ALWAYS when asked to CREATE A RULE or UPDATE A RULE or taught a lesson from the user that should be retained as a new rule for Cursor"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{}, :file-globs [".cursor/rules/**/*.mdc"]},
               :severity :minor,
               :knowledge-content
               "# LLM Rules Format\n\n## Core Structure\n\n```mdc\n---\ndewey: \"NNN\"\ndescription: ACTION when TRIGGER to OUTCOME\nglobs: *.mdc\n---\n\n# Rule Title\n\n## Context\n- When to apply this rule\n- Prerequisites or conditions\n\n## Requirements\n- Concise, actionable items\n- Each requirement must be testable\n\n## Examples\n<example>\nGood concise example with explanation\n</example>\n\n<example type=\"invalid\">\nInvalid concise example with explanation\n</example>\n```\n\n## File Organization\n\n### Location\n\n- Root: `.cursor/rules/`\n- Extension: `.mdc`\n- Structure: `<category-slug>/<rule-slug>.mdc`\n- Dewey code: in frontmatter (`dewey: \"NNN\"`), not in the filename or path\n\n```zsh\n.cursor/rules/\n├── index.mdc           # Master catalog (dewey: \"000\")\n├── foundations/        # dewey 000-099\n├── languages/          # dewey 200-299\n├── frameworks/         # dewey 300-399\n├── workflows/          # dewey 700-799\n├── project/            # dewey 800-899\n└── meta/               # dewey 900-999\n```\n\n### Dewey Ranges\n\n```\n000-099  Foundations & Core Principles\n100-199  Development Environment & Tools\n200-299  Languages\n300-399  Frameworks & Platforms\n400-499  Testing & Quality\n500-599  Operations & Infrastructure\n600-699  Documentation\n700-799  Workflows & Processes\n800-899  Project-Specific\n900-999  Meta & Templates\n```\n\nPrivate rules: `_name.mdc` (underscore prefix)\n\n### Glob Pattern Examples\n\nCommon glob patterns for different rule types:\n\n- Core standards: .cursor/rules/*.mdc\n- Language rules: src/**/*.{js,ts}\n- Testing standards: **/*.test.{js,ts}\n- React components: src/components/**/*.tsx\n- Documentation: docs/**/*.md\n- Configuration files: *.config.{js,json}\n- Build artifacts: dist/**/*\n- Multiple extensions: src/**/*.{js,jsx,ts,tsx}\n- Multiple files: dist/**/*, docs/**/*.md\n\n## Required Fields\n\n### Frontmatter\n\n- description: ACTION TRIGGER OUTCOME format\n- globs: `glob pattern for files and folders`\n\n### Body\n\n- <version>X.Y.Z</version>\n- context: Usage conditions\n- requirements: Actionable items\n- examples: Both valid and invalid\n\n## Formatting Guidelines\n\n- Use Concise Markdown primarily\n- XML tags limited to:\n  - <example>\n  - <danger>\n  - <required>\n  - <rules>\n  - <rule>\n  - <critical>\n  - <version>\n- Always indent content within XML or nested XML tags by 2 spaces\n- Keep rules as short as possbile\n- Use Mermaid syntax if it will be shorter or clearer than describing a complex rule\n- Use Emojis where appropriate to convey meaning that will improve rule understanding by the AI Agent\n- Keep examples as short as possible to clearly convey the positive or negative example\n\n## AI Optimization Tips\n\n1. Use precise, deterministic ACTION TRIGGER OUTCOME format in descriptions\n2. Provide concise positive and negative example of rule application in practice\n3. Optimize for AI context window efficiency\n4. Remove any non-essential or redundant information\n5. Use standard glob patterns without quotes (e.g., *.js, src/**/*.ts)\n\n## AI Context Efficiency\n\n1. Keep frontmatter description under 120 characters (or less) while maintaining clear intent for rule selection by AI AGent\n2. Limit examples to essential patterns only\n3. Use hierarchical structure for quick parsing\n4. Remove redundant information across sections\n5. Maintain high information density with minimal tokens\n6. Focus on machine-actionable instructions over human explanations\n\n<critical>\n  - NEVER include verbose explanations or redundant context that increases AI token overhead\n  - Keep file as short and to the point as possible BUT NEVER at the expense of sacrificing \n    rule impact and usefulness for the AI Agent.\n  - the front matter can ONLY have the fields description and globs.\n</critical>",
               :id :std/rule-format,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "900",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (900): Use ALWAYS when asked to CREATE A RULE or UPDATE A RULE or taught a lesson from the user that should be retained as a new rule for Cursor"}
        #:rule{:title "Rust style and idioms",
               :agent-behavior
               "See also: `foundations/stratified-design` and `foundations/simple-made-easy` — those rules apply in Rust\nwithout exception. This file covers Rust-specific idioms that sit on top of those foundations.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :audit,
                :message "Standard: Rust style and idioms"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:review :implement},
                :file-globs ["**/*.rs" "**/Cargo.toml"]},
               :severity :minor,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Rust style guide\n\nSee also: `foundations/stratified-design` and `foundations/simple-made-easy` — those rules apply in Rust\nwithout exception. This file covers Rust-specific idioms that sit on top of those foundations.\n\n## Crate and module structure\n\n- Use Cargo workspaces with small crates and explicit boundaries.\n- Keep domain logic in crates that have no dependency on transport or framework crates (Axum, tonic,\n  etc.). Adapters live in their own crates.\n- Keep FFI surfaces narrow, stable, and JSON-schema aligned.\n- Prefer `struct`/`enum` data modeling over trait-heavy abstractions. Reach for traits when you need\n  open polymorphism; do not create trait hierarchies as a substitute for thinking about data shapes.\n- One major type per module is a useful default; group supporting types nearby, not scattered.\n\n## Naming\n\nFollow standard Rust conventions:\n\n| Item | Convention | Example |\n|------|-----------|---------|\n| Types (struct, enum, trait) | `UpperCamelCase` | `CautionContext` |\n| Functions and methods | `snake_case` | `evaluate_regime` |\n| Local variables | `snake_case` | `family_buckets` |\n| Modules | `snake_case` | `rule_engine` |\n| Constants and statics | `SCREAMING_SNAKE_CASE` | `MAX_RETRIES` |\n| Type parameters | Short `UpperCamelCase` | `T`, `Err` |\n\nUse long, descriptive names for locals — code completion makes short names a false economy. Default\nvariable names to use consistently:\n\n- `res` — result being built\n- `ctx` — context bundle\n- `acc` — accumulator\n- `it` — iteration variable when the name does not matter\n\nAvoid ad-hoc abbreviations. Use the established set (`db`, `ctx`, `acc`) or spell it out.\n\nNames that clash with keywords: mangle rather than use raw identifiers (`r#`):\n\n```\ncrate  → krate\nenum   → enum_\nfn     → func\nimpl   → imp\nmod    → module\nstruct → strukt\ntrait  → trait_\ntype   → ty\n```\n\n## Data-driven policy patterns\n\nCentralize business rules as data, not scattered conditionals — the Rust application of\nsimple-made-easy's \"rules live in one place\" principle.\n\n### Context structs\n\nBundle related evaluation inputs into a named struct. Functions that share the same inputs should\nshare the same context type.\n\n```rust\n// Good: context bundles related state\nstruct CautionContext<'a> {\n    style_id: &'a str,\n    regime: &'a str,\n    family_buckets: BTreeMap<&'a str, Option<&'a str>>,\n}\n\n// Bad: six loose parameters threaded through call chains\nfn evaluate(regime: &str, conc: bool, families: &[F], confidence: &str, ...) -> R\n```\n\n### Rule tables over conditional chains\n\nReplace `if`/`match` chains that encode policy with `const` rule tables. Each entry is a\npredicate + payload. This applies equally to large `match` expressions — when the arms are\nencoding policy, pull them into a table.\n\n```rust\n// Good: policy as data\nstruct CautionRule {\n    predicate: fn(&CautionContext) -> bool,\n    message: &'static str,\n}\n\nconst CAUTION_RULES: &[CautionRule] = &[\n    CautionRule { predicate: |ctx| ctx.family_is_red(\"valuation\"), message: CAUTION_VALUATION },\n    CautionRule { predicate: |ctx| ctx.regime == \"defensive\",     message: CAUTION_EDUCATIONAL },\n];\n\nfn cautions(ctx: &CautionContext) -> Vec<String> {\n    CAUTION_RULES.iter().filter(|r| (r.predicate)(ctx)).map(|r| r.message.to_string()).collect()\n}\n\n// Bad: scattered if-chains\nif family_is_red(\"valuation\") { cautions.push(...) }\nif family_is_red(\"yield_curve\") { cautions.push(...) }\nif regime == \"defensive\" { cautions.push(...) }\n```\n\n### Resolution structs\n\nWhen a function selects from alternatives, return a named struct — not a tuple.\n\n```rust\n// Good\nstruct PlaybookResolution { regime: String, thesis: String, targets: BTreeMap<String, f64> }\n\n// Bad: positional tuple leaking internal ordering\nlet (regime, thesis, targets, id, rationale) = resolve(...);\n```\n\n### String constants\n\nAll user-facing and advisory text lives in a `strings.rs` module as `pub const`. Domain logic\nreferences `crate::strings::*` — never inline string literals in business logic.\n\n## Error handling\n\n### Library crates: use `thiserror`\n\nDefine typed error enums for each crate. `thiserror` derives `std::error::Error`, `Display`, and\n`From` with minimal boilerplate:\n\n```rust\n#[derive(Debug, thiserror::Error)]\npub enum ServiceError {\n    #[error(\"Database error: {0}\")]\n    Db(#[from] DbError),\n    #[error(\"Invalid data: {0}\")]\n    InvalidData(String),\n    #[error(transparent)]\n    Serialization(#[from] serde_json::Error),\n}\n```\n\nFor layered systems, nest error enums with `#[from]` to preserve context at each boundary.\n\n### Binary crates: `anyhow` is acceptable\n\n`anyhow::Result` is appropriate in `main`, CLI entry points, and test helpers where ergonomic\npropagation matters more than precise error types. Do not use `anyhow` in library crates — it\nerases type context that callers need.\n\nUse `anyhow::format_err!` rather than `anyhow::anyhow` (less stuttering).\n\n### General error rules\n\n- Prefer `Result`; avoid `panic!` except for genuine programmer errors (`unreachable!`, `todo!`,\n  test assertions).\n- Do not use `.unwrap()` or `.expect()` in production code paths. Prefer `let Ok(x) = ... else`\n  for early returns, `?` for bubbling, or combinator methods (`unwrap_or`, `unwrap_or_else`).\n- Use `?` to propagate errors rather than verbose `match` chains.\n- Async errors that cross `.await` boundaries must implement `Send + Sync + 'static`.\n- Separate parse failures, transport failures, and stale-cache behavior explicitly — do not collapse\n  them into a single opaque error variant.\n- Test error paths: check `err.to_string()` when `PartialEq` is not available.\n\n## Type idioms\n\n### Prefer general borrowed types on function boundaries\n\nUse the more general borrowed form:\n\n| Prefer | Over |\n|--------|------|\n| `&str` | `&String` |\n| `&[T]` | `&Vec<T>` |\n| `Option<&T>` | `&Option<T>` |\n| `&Path` | `&PathBuf` |\n\n### `Copy` types\n\nDerive `Copy` for small plain-data structs (up to ~3 words / 24 bytes) whose fields are all `Copy`.\nDo not derive `Copy` on types containing `String`, `Vec`, or other heap-owning fields.\n\n### Constructors\n\nPrefer `#[derive(Default)]` over a zero-argument `new()` when the zero value is correct. Avoid\ninventing \"dummy\" default states just to satisfy `Default`.\n\n### Getters\n\nIf a field has an invariant, make it `private`, enforce it in the constructor, and expose a getter\nthat returns a borrowed form:\n\n```rust\n// Good\nfn first_name(&self) -> &str { self.first_name.as_str() }\nfn middle_name(&self) -> Option<&str> { self.middle_name.as_ref() }\n\n// Bad — clones unnecessarily, or leaks container type\nfn first_name(&self) -> String { self.first_name.clone() }\nfn middle_name(&self) -> &Option<String> { &self.middle_name }\n```\n\nNever provide setters. If mutation is needed after construction, provide a builder or use\n`pub` fields when there are no invariants to protect.\n\n## `impl Trait` vs generics vs `dyn Trait`\n\n- Prefer `impl Trait` in function arguments when the caller's concrete type is unimportant and you\n  want zero-cost static dispatch without spelling out a type parameter.\n- Use explicit `<T: Trait>` when you need to name `T` elsewhere in the signature (return type,\n  multiple parameters of the same type).\n- Reserve `dyn Trait` for cases where you genuinely need runtime polymorphism: heterogeneous\n  collections, plugin boundaries, or abstracting internals behind a stable interface. Avoid boxing\n  too early inside structs.\n- Prefer `&dyn Trait` over `Box<dyn Trait>` when ownership is not required.\n- Avoid `AsRef` polymorphism in non-library code — it inflates compile times without meaningful\n  benefit at call sites.\n\n## Functions and control flow\n\n### Preconditions in types\n\nExpress preconditions in types; do not check in the callee what the caller should have provided:\n\n```rust\n// Good — caller must supply a Walrus\nfn frobnicate(walrus: Walrus) { ... }\n\n// Bad — callee silently no-ops on None\nfn frobnicate(walrus: Option<Walrus>) {\n    let Some(walrus) = walrus else { return };\n    ...\n}\n```\n\n### Early returns\n\nUse early returns to reduce cognitive nesting. Use `return Err(...)` explicitly rather than `Err(...)?`:\n\n```rust\n// Good\nfn foo() -> Option<Bar> {\n    if !condition() {\n        return None;\n    }\n    Some(...)\n}\n```\n\n### Functions with many parameters\n\nReplace boolean flags and long parameter lists with a `Config` struct:\n\n```rust\n// Good\npub struct AnnotationConfig {\n    pub binary_target: bool,\n    pub annotate_runnables: bool,\n    pub annotate_impls: bool,\n}\n\npub fn annotations(db: &RootDatabase, file_id: FileId, config: AnnotationConfig) -> Vec<Annotation>\n\n// Bad\npub fn annotations(db: &RootDatabase, file_id: FileId, binary_target: bool,\n                   annotate_runnables: bool, annotate_impls: bool) -> Vec<Annotation>\n```\n\nDo not implement `Default` for `Config` structs; require callers to be explicit about every field.\n\n### Avoid \"doer\" objects\n\nPrefer a plain function over a struct constructed solely to call one method:\n\n```rust\n// Good\ndo_thing(arg1, arg2);\n\n// Bad\nThingDoer::new(arg1, arg2).do();\n```\n\nWhen an operation has genuine internal state, hide the struct behind a public function:\n\n```rust\npub fn do_thing(arg1: Arg1, arg2: Arg2) -> Res {\n    Ctx { arg1, arg2 }.run()\n}\n```\n\n### Helper variables\n\nIntroduce named variables for complex conditions rather than inline expressions. Single-use\nvariables are cognitively cheap and aid debugging.\n\n## Linting\n\n- Keep `cargo clippy --all-targets --all-features -- -D warnings` clean.\n- Fix warnings; do not silence them with `#[allow(...)]` unless you understand the lint and document\n  why suppression is correct. Prefer `#[expect(...)]` with a comment — it re-warns if the lint\n  becomes inapplicable.\n- Do not add `#[allow(dead_code)]` to suppress incomplete work; remove the dead code or add a\n  tracked issue.\n- Configure lint levels in `Cargo.toml` `[workspace.lints]` rather than per-file attributes.\n\n## Memory and allocation\n\n- Borrow (`&T`) rather than clone (`T::clone()`) by default. Clone deliberately when you need\n  an owned copy.\n- Do not clone inside iterator chains — use `.cloned()` or `.copied()` at the chain boundary.\n- Avoid collecting into a `Vec` when an iterator suffices.\n- For recursive collection-building functions, use an accumulator parameter instead of returning\n  and merging fresh collections on each recursion.\n- Avoid monomorphizing large functions across crate boundaries — use a thin generic wrapper that\n  delegates to a `&dyn Fn` implementation.\n\n## Import style\n\nGroup imports separated by blank lines in this order: `std`, external crates, `crate::`, `super::`\n/ `self::`. Re-exports should be rare and placed after imports. Avoid local `use MyEnum::*`.\n\n## Documentation\n\n- Write `///` doc comments on all public items (functions, structs, traits, enums, constants).\n- Include a `# Errors` section when a function returns `Result`, a `# Panics` section when it can\n  panic, and a `# Safety` section when it contains `unsafe`.\n- Write runnable `# Examples` in doc comments — they become `cargo test` test cases.\n- Use `//!` module/crate-level comments at the top of `lib.rs` or `mod.rs`.\n- Inline `//` comments explain *why*, not *what*. Start comments with a capital letter and end with\n  a period. Named comment kinds (`// SAFETY:`, `// CONTEXT:`, `// INVARIANT:`) signal intent.\n- Do not leave `// TODO` without a tracked issue reference.\n\n## Testing\n\n- Prefer fixture-based parity tests for contract compatibility (golden files, snapshot testing).\n- Add focused unit tests for pure domain functions: reducers, evaluators, regime logic.\n- Keep synthetic tests small and deterministic. Use `cargo insta` for snapshot tests.\n- Tests must exercise error paths, not just happy paths.\n- Do not use `#[should_panic]`; check `Err`/`None` explicitly.\n- Do not `#[ignore]` tests; assert the wrong behavior with a `// FIXME` if it is not yet correct.\n- Test snippets should be minimal — remove boilerplate not relevant to what is being tested.\n\n## What NOT to do\n\n- Do not scatter policy conditionals across modules. See rule tables above.\n- Do not use `unwrap`/`expect` in production call paths.\n- Do not use `anyhow` in library crates.\n- Do not add `#[allow(dead_code)]` to paper over incomplete work.\n- Do not create trait hierarchies as a substitute for reasoning about data shapes.\n- Do not clone prematurely inside loops or iterator chains.\n- Do not use `Box<dyn Trait>` inside structs unless runtime polymorphism is genuinely required.\n- Do not mix domain logic with transport concerns in the same crate (see stratified-design).",
               :id :std/rust,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "230",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (230): Rust style and idioms"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Simple Made Easy — choose constructs with simpler artifacts, not easier authoring",
               :agent-behavior
               "- When proposing a design, include:\n- When editing code that’s overly complex:\n  - Suggest a “data first” rewrite of the hot path.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message
                "Standard: Simple Made Easy — choose constructs with simpler artifacts, not easier authoring"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement}},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Simple Made Easy (ALWAYS)\n\nOptimize for **simple artifacts** (unbraided, decoupled), not for what is **easy** (familiar, at hand).\nUsers live with the artifact, not the authoring experience.\n\n> “Simplicity is a prerequisite for reliability.” — Dijkstra  \n> Simple = one braid (uncomplected). Easy = familiar/near. Choose simple.\n\n## Decision rubric\n\nWhen choosing designs/constructs, prefer the option that **reduces intertwining** of concerns—even if it’s less familiar.\n\n- **Values over state**: prefer immutable values and pure functions; make state explicit, local, and small.\n- **Data over syntax**: represent information as plain data (maps, vectors, sets). Avoid DSL-ish micro-syntaxes unless necessary.\n- **Functions over methods**: favor small, stateless functions and namespaces over deep OO hierarchies.\n- **A-la-carte polymorphism**: choose open, decoupled dispatch (protocols/typeclasses/interfaces) over\n                               inheritance and giant enums/switches.\n- **Declarative over imperative**: use set/relational operations, queries, and rules for “what,” not “how.”\n- **Queues over calls (when/where)**: decouple time/place with message queues or async boundaries; don’t make A know B unnecessarily.\n- **Rules live in one place (why)**: centralize policy in data/rules tables or a rules engine, not scattered conditionals.\n\n## What / Who / How / When / Where / Why — keep separate\n\n- **What**: operations (names and contracts); small specs (inputs/outputs) live with the function/module.\n- **Who**: concrete implementers/adapters wired via DI; no leaking details across boundaries.\n- **How**: implementations chosen behind interfaces/ports; keep replaceable.\n- **When/Where**: scheduling, retries, concurrency, and topology belong at edges (adapter/config).\n- **Why**: policies and rules centralized; treat as data.\n\n## State & concurrency\n\n- Treat state as hazardous material:\n  - Justify it, minimize scope, isolate at the edge.\n  - Model with managed references/STM/actors only when true concurrency requires it.\n- Prefer idempotent, deterministic operations; make time and randomness injectable.\n\n## Change & debugging\n\n- Smaller surface area ⇒ fewer joints to break. Strive for modules you can reason about locally.\n- Reasonability beats tooling: if understanding requires a global tour, simplify the design.\n- Tests are nets, not wings: don’t rely on them to compensate for tangled designs.\n\n## PR checklist (Author & Reviewer)\n\n- **Simplicity**: Does this reduce entanglement vs alternatives? What did we *remove*?\n- **Boundaries**: Are What/Who/How/When/Where/Why separated?\n- **Data**: Is information represented as plain data, not hidden in code constructs?\n- **State**: Is state minimized, localized, and explicit? Why must it exist?\n- **Policy**: Are rules centralized and declarative?\n- **Swapability**: Can we replace implementations without touching callers?\n- **Evidence**: Include a short note comparing the “easy but complex” option you rejected.\n\n## Agent behavior\n\n- When proposing a design, include:\n  1) A short “simple vs easy” comparison (2–3 bullets).  \n  2) The minimal set of pure functions and data structures.  \n  3) Where any state/concurrency is confined and why it’s necessary.  \n  4) A rules/policy section expressed as data (table/map) if applicable.\n- When editing code that’s overly complex:\n  - Suggest a “data first” rewrite of the hot path.\n  - Extract policy into a dedicated rules module or data file.\n  - Replace switch/if jungles with open polymorphism where beneficial.\n\n## Red flags to push back on\n\n- Deep inheritance trees; giant God objects/services.\n- Conditionals scattered across the codebase encoding policy ad hoc.\n- ORM-driven domain models leaking persistence concerns everywhere.\n- Actor systems chosen “by default” where simple queues/calls suffice.\n- Tight coupling to frameworks in core logic (non-replaceable code).\n\n## Accept that simple ≠ fewer things\n\nIt’s okay if we end up with *more but smaller* modules. We’re minimizing braiding, not counting files.",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/simple-made-easy,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "010",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (010): Simple Made Easy — choose constructs with simpler artifacts, not easier authoring"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Follow normative specs (N1-N6) for all implementation and maintain spec governance",
               :agent-behavior "<version>0.1.0</version>",
               :enforcement
               {:action :audit,
                :message
                "Standard: Follow normative specs (N1-N6) for all implementation and maintain spec governance"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement},
                :file-globs ["specs/**/*.md"]},
               :severity :minor,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Specification Standards\n\n<version>0.1.0</version>\n\n## Context\n\nminiforge uses 6 normative specifications (N1-N6) that define ALL contractual requirements. All\nimplementation MUST conform to these specs. Specs extracted from strategic vision, NOT from code.\n\n**Entry point:** `specs/SPEC_INDEX.md`\n\n## Hierarchy\n\n```zsh\nspecs/\n├── SPEC_INDEX.md          # START HERE - authoritative entry point\n├── README.md              # Implementation guide\n├── normative/             # N1-N6 (MUST/SHALL only)\n├── informative/           # Guidance (no MUST/SHALL)\n├── examples/              # Reference implementations\n└── deprecated/            # Superseded (ignore)\n```\n\n## Requirements\n\n### When Reading Specs\n\n<required>\n- ALWAYS start with `specs/SPEC_INDEX.md` for overview\n- Read normative specs (N1-N6) for MUST/SHALL requirements\n- NEVER use deprecated/ directory content\n- Cross-reference: specs link to each other\n- Use examples/ for concrete patterns\n</required>\n\n### When Implementing\n\n<required>\n- Implementation MUST conform to all 6 normative specs\n- Event emission MUST follow N3 (Event Stream)\n- Evidence bundles MUST follow N6 (Evidence & Provenance)\n- Workflow execution MUST follow N2 (Workflows)\n- Policy packs MUST follow N4 (Policy Packs)\n- CLI/TUI/API MUST follow N5 (Interface Standard)\n- Architecture MUST follow N1 (Core Architecture)\n</required>\n\n### When Amending Specs\n\n<required>\n- NO new normative spec files (only amend N1-N6)\n- New concepts MUST land in N1 or they're not real\n- New runtime data MUST land in N3 or N6 or it's unobservable\n- New UX features MUST point to contract in N3/N5/N6\n- Normative specs MUST use RFC 2119 keywords (MUST/SHALL/SHOULD/MAY)\n- Informative docs MUST NOT use RFC 2119 keywords\n</required>\n\n### Spec Extraction Source\n\n<critical>\n- Extract specs from strategic documents (software-factory-vision.md, oss-paid-roadmap.md)\n- NEVER extract specs from implementation code\n- Specs define what MUST be built, not what happens to exist\n- Code conforms to specs, not the reverse\n</critical>\n\n## Six Normative Specs\n\n| Spec | File | Purpose | Key Contracts |\n|------|------|---------|---------------|\n| N1 | `N1-architecture.md` | Core concepts, layering | 12 nouns, 3-layer architecture, Polylith boundaries |\n| N2 | `N2-workflows.md` | Workflow execution | Phase graph, inner/outer loops, gate contract |\n| N3 | `N3-event-stream.md` | Event stream & observability | 9 event types, SSE/WebSocket, ordering guarantees |\n| N4 | `N4-policy-packs.md` | Policy packs & gates | Semantic intent validation, check/repair contract |\n| N5 | `N5-cli-tui-api.md` | CLI/TUI/API interface | Command taxonomy, TUI views, streaming endpoints |\n| N6 | `N6-evidence-provenance.md` | Evidence & provenance | Evidence bundles, artifact provenance, semantic validation |\n\n**Most leverageful:** N3 (Event Stream) and N6 (Evidence & Provenance) - everything builds on these.\n\n## Governance Rules\n\n**Prevent spec explosion:**\n\n1. **No new normative spec files** - Only amend N1-N6\n2. **Every new concept must land in N1** - Or it's not real\n3. **Every new runtime datum must land in N3 or N6** - Or it's unobservable\n4. **Every UX feature must point to a contract** - Or it's just a mock\n5. **Roadmaps never contain contracts** - They link to specs\n\n## Examples\n\n<example>\n✅ GOOD: Implementing event emission\n\n```clojure\n;; Following N3 event schema\n(emit-event {:event/type :agent/status\n             :event/id (uuid)\n             :event/timestamp (Instant/now)\n             :event/version \"1.0.0\"\n             :workflow/id workflow-id\n             :event/sequence-number (next-seq)\n             :agent/id :implementer\n             :status/type :generating\n             :message \"Generating Terraform code...\"})\n```\n\nAgent emits events following N3 schema exactly. Event stream is product infrastructure.\n</example>\n\n<example>\n✅ GOOD: Semantic intent validation\n\n```clojure\n;; Following N6 semantic validation\n(validate-intent {:declared :import\n                  :actual-creates 0    ; MUST be 0 for :import\n                  :actual-destroys 0}) ; MUST be 0 for :import\n;; => {:passed? true}\n\n(validate-intent {:declared :import\n                  :actual-creates 3    ; VIOLATION!\n                  :actual-destroys 0})\n;; => {:passed? false :violation \"Declared IMPORT but creates 3 resources\"}\n```\n\nSemantic validation catches intent violations (declared IMPORT but code creates resources).\n</example>\n\n<example type=\"invalid\">\n❌ BAD: Extracting spec from code\n\n```clojure\n;; Reading implementation to write spec\n(read-file \"miniforge/components/agent/core.clj\")\n;; Then writing spec based on what code does\n```\n\nNEVER extract specs from code. Specs define requirements, code implements them.\nExtract from strategic documents (software-factory-vision.md, oss-paid-roadmap.md).\n</example>\n\n<example type=\"invalid\">\n❌ BAD: Creating new normative spec\n\n```zsh\nspecs/normative/N7-new-feature.md  # WRONG!\n```\n\nNO new normative specs. Amend existing N1-N6 only. This prevents spec explosion.\n</example>\n\n<example type=\"invalid\">\n❌ BAD: Using MUST/SHALL in informative docs\n\n```markdown\n# Informative Guide\n\nThe TUI MUST display workflow progress...  # WRONG in informative!\n```\n\nOnly normative specs (N1-N6) use RFC 2119 keywords. Informative docs use descriptive language.\n</example>\n\n## Conformance\n\nImplementation is conformant if:\n\n- ✅ Events follow N3 schema, maintain sequencing, support replay\n- ✅ Evidence bundles follow N6 schema, immutable, complete provenance\n- ✅ Workflows execute N2 phase graph, inner/outer loops work\n- ✅ Policy packs follow N4 schema, semantic validation works\n- ✅ CLI/TUI/API match N5 taxonomy, event streaming works\n- ✅ Architecture follows N1 layering, components respect boundaries\n\n**Enforcement:** Schema validation + integration tests + conformance suite\n\n## Quick Reference\n\n**Building agents?** → N3 (emit events), N6 (create evidence)\n**Building CLI/TUI?** → N5 (interface), N3 (consume events)\n**Building policy packs?** → N4 (pack schema, gate contract)\n**Understanding execution?** → N2 (workflows), N6 (semantic validation)\n**Architecture questions?** → N1 (core concepts, layering)\n\n## Related Rules\n\n- `001-stratified-design.mdc` - Layering principles (complements N1)\n- `721-pr-documentation.mdc` - PR docs (includes spec conformance notes)",
               :id :std/specification-standards,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "020",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (020): Follow normative specs (N1-N6) for all implementation and maintain spec governance"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Testing standards — factory functions, same code quality as production, no duplication",
               :agent-behavior
               "When writing tests:\n1. Before writing the first `deftest`, ask: what factory functions does this test file need?\n2. Extract them immediately at Layer 0, not after the fact.\n3. Apply the same code review lens to tests as to production code — no magic numbers, no nested conditionals, no raw string literals.\n4. If a test helper is used in more than one test file in the same component, move it to a shared `fixtures.clj`.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message
                "Standard: Testing standards — factory functions, same code quality as production, no duplication"},
               :applies-to {:phases #{:verify :implement}},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Testing Standards (ALWAYS)\n\n**Test code is production code.** Every standard that applies to implementation code applies to test code. No exceptions.\n\n## Factory functions over inline maps\n\nTest data construction must use factory functions. Never build event maps, entity maps, or request fixtures inline.\n\n```clojure\n;; BAD — inline map construction repeated in every test\n(def event1\n  {:event/type      :workflow/started\n   :event/id        (random-uuid)\n   :event/timestamp (java.util.Date/from (java.time.Instant/parse \"2026-01-01T00:00:00Z\"))\n   :workflow/id     \"wf-123\"})\n\n;; Same map rebuilt again in another test\n{:event/type      :workflow/completed\n :event/id        (random-uuid)\n :event/timestamp (java.util.Date/from (java.time.Instant/parse \"2026-01-01T01:00:00Z\"))\n :workflow/id     \"wf-123\"}\n\n;; GOOD — factory function\n(defn- parse-ts [s]\n  (java.util.Date/from (java.time.Instant/parse s)))\n\n(defn- wf-event\n  [event-type wf-id timestamp & {:as extra}]\n  (merge {:event/type      event-type\n          :event/id        (random-uuid)\n          :event/timestamp (parse-ts timestamp)\n          :workflow/id     wf-id}\n         extra))\n\n;; Usage — readable and DRY\n(wf-event :workflow/started    \"wf-123\" \"2026-01-01T00:00:00Z\")\n(wf-event :workflow/completed  \"wf-123\" \"2026-01-01T01:00:00Z\" :workflow/status :success)\n(wf-event :workflow/phase-started \"wf-123\" \"2026-01-01T00:05:00Z\" :workflow/phase :implement)\n```\n\n**When to create a factory:**\n- Any test data map constructed more than once — extract immediately\n- Any map with more than 3 fields — factory even if used once (for readability)\n- Any map that varies by a few fields across tests — factory with keyword args for the varying parts\n\n## Same structural standards as production code\n\nTests are organized by the same stratified-design and code quality rules:\n\n- **Layered structure**: Layer 0 for helpers and factories, Layer 1 for individual tests, Layer 2 for integration scenarios\n- **No nested conditionals** in test helpers\n- **No magic numbers**: extract constants (`(def ^:private timeout-ms 5000)`)\n- **No raw strings** in test data that represents user-facing copy — use the same message keys\n- **Named test helpers**: a function that sets up a specific scenario should have a clear, descriptive name\n- **DRY**: shared test helpers for a component go in a `test_helpers.clj` or `fixtures.clj` alongside the tests\n\n## Test file layout\n\n```clojure\n(ns ai.miniforge.foo.bar-test\n  (:require [clojure.test :refer [deftest is testing]]\n            [ai.miniforge.foo.bar :as sut]))\n\n;------------------------------------------------------------------------------ Layer 0\n;; Test fixtures and factories\n\n(def ^:private sample-id \"test-wf-001\")\n\n(defn- make-event [type & {:as extra}]\n  (merge {:event/type type :event/id (random-uuid)} extra))\n\n;------------------------------------------------------------------------------ Layer 1\n;; Unit tests\n\n(deftest test-specific-behavior\n  (testing \"given condition → expected result\"\n    (is (= expected (sut/fn-under-test input)))))\n```\n\n## What tests must NOT do\n\n- **No LLM calls**: mock or stub at the interface boundary\n- **No filesystem reads** (except integration tests explicitly marked as such): use `with-open` on temp files or in-memory fixtures\n- **No real network calls**: stub HTTP clients\n- **No sleep**: use deterministic time injection or fast-forward mechanisms\n- **No `println` in test bodies**: use `testing` blocks with descriptive strings\n\n## Naming conventions\n\n- Test ns: `<component-ns>-test` or `<component-ns>.<concern>-test`\n- Test fn: `test-<behavior-under-test>` (not `test-function-name`)\n- `testing` description: `\"given <setup> → <expected outcome>\"` format\n\n## Agent behavior\n\nWhen writing tests:\n1. Before writing the first `deftest`, ask: what factory functions does this test file need?\n2. Extract them immediately at Layer 0, not after the fact.\n3. Apply the same code review lens to tests as to production code — no magic numbers, no nested conditionals, no raw string literals.\n4. If a test helper is used in more than one test file in the same component, move it to a shared `fixtures.clj`.\n\n## Anti-patterns to reject\n\n- Inline map construction that repeats more than once\n- `(Thread/sleep 100)` in tests — eliminate or use test-controlled time\n- `(str \"test-\" (random-uuid))` repeated everywhere — extract to a factory\n- Tests named after functions: `test-wf-status` → name for behavior: `test-stale-workflow-detection`\n- 100-line `deftest` functions — split into smaller, focused tests",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/standards,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "400",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (400): Testing standards — factory functions, same code quality as production, no duplication"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Stratified Design — enforce one-way dependencies and clear data flow",
               :agent-behavior
               "- Before writing code for a feature, output:\n  - A short stratified plan (modules, their stratum, and allowed dependencies).\n  - The ports/interfaces to be introduced or reused.\n- When editing existing code:\n  - Detect and call out any “upward” import or cross-strata leakage.\n  - If a cycle is present, propose a minimal refactor (move interface “down,” split module, or add adapter).",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message
                "Standard: Stratified Design — enforce one-way dependencies and clear data flow"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement}},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Stratified Design (ALWAYS)\n\nUse a single-direction DAG for code dependencies. No cycles. Modules only depend “down” the stack. Keep data flow explicit.\n\n## Canonical strata\n\nOrder from innermost (most stable) to outermost (most volatile). Depend only on strata at the same level or below:\n\n0. **Foundations** — pure utilities, types, data schemas, constants (no I/O)\n1. **Domain** — business rules, pure functions, policies, invariants (no I/O)\n2. **Application / Use-Cases** — orchestration of domain operations, ports (no infra details)\n3. **Adapters** — HTTP controllers, CLIs, schedulers, event handlers, API/DTO mapping\n4. **Infrastructure** — DB/ORM, queues, caches, cloud SDKs, filesystems, external services\n\n> **Allowed imports:**<br> \n> `Adapters → Application → Domain → Foundations` and <br>\n> `Infrastructure → (Application|Domain|Foundations)` via **ports/interfaces** only. No “upward” imports.\n\n## Principles\n\n- **No cycles**: reject any PR that introduces an import/namespace cycle.\n- **Pure core**: Domain must be free of I/O, frameworks, and runtime state. Inject effects at edges.\n- **Ports & Adapters**: Define *ports* (interfaces) in the Application layer; implement *adapters* in   Adapters/Infrastructure.\n- **Boundary DTOs**: Translate at the edge; don’t leak transport/DB types into Domain.\n- **Data flow clarity**: Inbound Adapter → Application (use-case) → Domain → (ports) → Outbound Adapter.<br>\n Never reverse this flow.\n- **Policy location**: Domain for timeless rules; Application for workflow; Adapters for translation;<br>\nInfrastructure for mechanics.\n\n## When designing/implementing\n\n1. **Sketch the DAG**: list modules by stratum and draw arrows downward only.\n2. **Name your ports**: e.g., `UserRepo`, `PaymentGateway`. Domain never knows the concrete.\n3. **Decouple by data**: pass plain data structures across boundaries; map near edges.\n4. **Confine effects**: create thin effectful functions at the outermost layer; keep inner layers referentially transparent.\n5. **Prove it**: in PRs, include a tiny import graph (or summary) showing no upward edges/no cycles.\n\n## Agent behavior\n\n- Before writing code for a feature, output:\n  - A short stratified plan (modules, their stratum, and allowed dependencies).\n  - The ports/interfaces to be introduced or reused.\n- When editing existing code:\n  - Detect and call out any “upward” import or cross-strata leakage.\n  - If a cycle is present, propose a minimal refactor (move interface “down,” split module, or add adapter).\n\n## Anti-patterns to reject\n\n- Domain importing framework/ORM/cloud SDKs.\n- Adapters calling Infrastructure directly without going through Application ports.\n- “God modules” mixing controller logic, business rules, and DB calls.\n- Cross-strata singletons/service-locators.\n\n## (Optional) Enforcement hooks (suggest when asked)\n\n- TS/JS: dependency-cruiser rules to forbid upward imports & cycles.\n- Python: import-linter contracts for layered architecture.\n- Clojure: clj-kondo + namespace graph check to fail on cycles.",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/stratified-design,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "001",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (001): Stratified Design — enforce one-way dependencies and clear data flow"}
        #:rule{:title "Swift and SwiftUI style and idioms",
               :agent-behavior
               "See also: `foundations/stratified-design` and `foundations/simple-made-easy` — those rules apply in\nSwift without exception. This file covers Swift-specific idioms that sit on top of those foundations.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :audit,
                :message
                "Standard: Swift and SwiftUI style and idioms"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:review :implement},
                :file-globs ["**/*.swift" "**/Package.swift"]},
               :severity :minor,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Swift and SwiftUI style guide\n\nSee also: `foundations/stratified-design` and `foundations/simple-made-easy` — those rules apply in\nSwift without exception. This file covers Swift-specific idioms that sit on top of those foundations.\n\n## General\n\n- Prefer value types (`struct`, `enum`) and immutable data flow. Reach for `class` when identity\n  semantics or reference sharing are genuinely required.\n- Use `async`/`await` for network and refresh flows; avoid callback pyramids.\n- Keep `swift build` and `swift test` green.\n- Mark all classes `final` unless you intend subclassing. Only use `open` when subclassing outside\n  the module is intentional.\n\n## Stratified view decomposition\n\nOrganize SwiftUI code into a one-way DAG of layers. Each file belongs to exactly one layer; imports\nflow downward only. (This is the Swift application of `foundations/stratified-design`.)\n\n| Layer | Contents | Example files |\n|-------|----------|---------------|\n| L0 Foundations | Pure display-mapping functions, data tables, formatters, design tokens | `DashboardDisplayMappers.swift`, `DesignSystem.swift` |\n| L1 Domain | Pure domain logic (assessment, classification, risk evaluation) | `HoldingRiskAssessment.swift` |\n| L2 Views | Small, single-purpose views composing L0/L1 | `SummaryCard.swift`, `FamilyViews.swift` |\n| L3 Workspaces | Tab-level containers composing L2 views | `ProfileWorkspace.swift`, `ContentView.swift` |\n\n### Concrete rules\n\n- **No God files**: a single `.swift` file should not contain all views for a tab or feature.\n  Decompose into focused files by domain concept.\n- **Extract computed properties**: break complex view bodies into named computed properties\n  (`portfolioDetailCard`, `sleeveBreakdown`). Each should fit in a single screen.\n- **Pure display mappers**: color selection, badge labels, formatting, and name lookups belong in\n  stateless functions or data tables — not inline in view bodies.\n- **Data tables over switch jungles**: replace `switch sleeve { case \"equities\": ... }` with\n  `Dictionary` lookups. Centralize the mapping. (See simple-made-easy \"rules live in one place\".)\n\n```swift\n// Good: data table\nprivate let sleeveNames: [String: String] = [\n    \"equities\": \"Equities\",\n    \"defensive_equities\": \"Defensive Equities\",\n    \"bonds\": \"Core Bonds\",\n]\nfunc sleeveDisplayName(_ key: String) -> String {\n    sleeveNames[key] ?? key.capitalized\n}\n\n// Bad: scattered switch\nswitch sleeve {\ncase \"equities\": return \"Equities\"\ncase \"defensive_equities\": return \"Defensive Equities\"\n// ...\n}\n```\n\n## Naming\n\nFollow the [Swift API Design Guidelines](https://swift.org/documentation/api-design-guidelines/#naming).\n\n- Include type information in UI component names to disambiguate at usage sites:\n  `settingsViewController: SettingsViewController`, `nameTextField: UITextField`.\n- Names should read as grammatical phrases at call sites. Omit redundant type names that are\n  already clear from context.\n- Use `lowerCamelCase` for properties and functions; `UpperCamelCase` for types and protocols.\n- Prefer American English spelling throughout.\n\n## Access control\n\n- **Default to `private`**. Anything that can be fully private should be. Widen access only when\n  there is a concrete need.\n- Use `private(set)` when external read access is needed but mutation should stay internal.\n- Use `fileprivate` only to share access between types in the same file, not as a substitute for\n  thinking about module boundaries.\n- Never write `internal` explicitly — it is the default and the annotation adds noise.\n- Only use `public` when a symbol must be used outside its defining module.\n\n## Optionals\n\n- Use optionals when the absence of a value has distinct meaning or when initialization is\n  genuinely deferred. Avoid them otherwise.\n- Do not make `Bool`s optional — a tri-state belongs in a named `enum`.\n- Do not make `Array`s optional unless an empty array has different semantics from nil.\n- Always handle unwrapping safely. Prefer `guard let` for early exit when a value is required;\n  prefer `if let` for branching when both paths have substance.\n- Avoid `flatMap` for optional unwrapping; use conditional binding instead.\n- Force-unwrap (`!`) is only acceptable when nil is a programmer error (e.g., storyboard outlets\n  that must exist). Add a comment explaining the invariant.\n\n```swift\n// Good: guard for required value, early exit\nguard let user = session.currentUser else {\n    return showLoginScreen()\n}\n\n// Bad: nested if-let pyramid\nif let session = session {\n    if let user = session.currentUser {\n        // ...\n    }\n}\n```\n\n## Control flow\n\n- Use `guard` for early returns when a condition must hold for the function to proceed. This keeps\n  the happy path unindented.\n- Prefer `guard let` / `guard let ... else` over nested `if let` chains.\n- Keep `switch` exhaustive; avoid `default:` clauses when the enum is under your control —\n  exhaustive switches catch future cases at compile time.\n\n## Protocols and extensions\n\n- Declare protocol conformance in a separate `extension` in the same file as the type:\n\n```swift\n// Good\nclass UserViewModel { ... }\n\nextension UserViewModel: Equatable {\n    static func == (lhs: UserViewModel, rhs: UserViewModel) -> Bool { ... }\n}\n\n// Bad — mixed in with the type body\nclass UserViewModel: Equatable {\n    static func == (...) { ... }\n    // ... other members ...\n}\n```\n\n- Use `MARK: - ProtocolName` inside conformance extensions for navigability.\n- Use protocols to wrap dependencies and enable substitution in tests.\n- Avoid `Any` and `AnyObject` — they discard type information and push errors to runtime. Prefer\n  a protocol with the required interface instead.\n- Only declare a protocol `open` when subclassing outside the module is intentional.\n\n## Computed properties vs methods\n\nUse a computed property when:\n- The computation is O(1) with no side effects.\n- The result depends only on instance state.\n- There is no meaningful failure mode.\n\nUse a method when:\n- The computation is expensive or has side effects.\n- The operation involves I/O, mutation of external state, or can fail.\n- The semantics are more \"do something\" than \"what is this thing\".\n\n## Closures\n\n- Use trailing closure syntax when the closure is the last argument and its purpose is clear from\n  context.\n- Always include explicit capture lists (`[weak self]`, `[unowned self]`) when capturing `self` in\n  a closure stored by the captured object, to prevent retain cycles.\n- Prefer `[weak self]` over `[unowned self]` unless you have a strong proof of lifetime.\n\n```swift\n// Good: trailing syntax with explicit capture list\nnetworkClient.fetch(request) { [weak self] result in\n    guard let self else { return }\n    self.handleResult(result)\n}\n```\n\n## File and type organization\n\n### One major type per file\n\nA file should contain one major type declaration. Supporting types (small enums, helper structs,\nassociated protocols) may accompany the primary type in the same file when they are not reused\nelsewhere.\n\n### Property and function ordering within a type\n\n```\n1. Property wrappers (@StateObject, @State, @AppStorage, @Binding, @ObservedObject)\n   grouped by wrapper kind, marked private\n2. Other stored properties — public/internal, then private\n3. Initializers\n4. deinit (if present, after last initializer)\n5. Overridden declarations (MARK: - SuperclassName)\n6. Protocol conformance (MARK: - ProtocolName)\n7. Type-specific declarations (MARK: - TypeName)\n   — public/internal, then private\n8. Extension conformances (each in a separate extension block)\n```\n\nUse `MARK: -` to separate the above groups when a file has overrides or conformances. Use `MARK:`\n(no dash) for secondary groupings inside a section.\n\n### Extension file naming\n\nGeneral-purpose extensions on external types live in their own files named\n`ExtendedType+Purpose.swift` (e.g., `Array+MergeSort.swift`).\n\n### SwiftUI file order\n\nWithin a SwiftUI `View`:\n1. Property wrappers grouped by type\n2. Other stored properties\n3. `init` (when explicitly written)\n4. `// MARK: - View` then `var body: some View`\n5. Computed property helpers\n\n## State management\n\n- Keep view models thin and explicit. Views receive data; they do not compute policy.\n- If a view needs to decide \"is this risky?\" or \"which regime applies?\", that logic belongs in L1\n  domain or in a lower-level core (e.g., Rust core over FFI).\n- Do not duplicate engine logic in Swift when another layer owns the policy.\n- Keep UI state (`@State`, `@StateObject`) scoped as locally as possible; lift state only when\n  multiple views genuinely share it.\n\n## Localization\n\nEvery user-facing string must go through a `Strings.*` namespace (backed by `NSLocalizedString` +\n`Localizable.strings`). No hardcoded English strings in views or view models. This is the Swift\napplication of simple-made-easy \"rules (and data) live in one place\".\n\n## Documentation and comments\n\n- Document all `internal` and higher access-level declarations with `///` doc comments.\n- `private` declarations may be documented for clarity but it is not required.\n- Document `enum` cases with a single line each. Document associated values as parameters.\n- Write comments to explain *why*, not *what*. Code that needs a comment to explain what it does\n  should usually be refactored into a named function or property.\n- Start comments with `//` followed by a space. Write complete sentences.\n- Do not leave `// TODO:` without a corresponding issue reference.\n\n## Testing\n\n- Use dependency injection (protocol types) to make view models and controllers testable in\n  isolation.\n- Test error and edge-case paths, not only happy paths.\n- Prefer small, focused unit tests for domain logic (L1 layer).\n- Integration tests cover the wiring between layers.\n\n## What NOT to do\n\n- Do not scatter policy conditionals across view files. Pull them into L0/L1 tables.\n- Do not use `Any` or `AnyObject` — use typed protocols.\n- Do not force-unwrap optionals in production code without documenting the invariant.\n- Do not put business logic into view bodies or computed view properties.\n- Do not mix UI state and network/storage concerns in the same type (see stratified-design).\n- Do not use `default:` in `switch` statements over enums you control.\n- Do not introduce retain cycles by capturing `self` strongly in stored closures.\n- Do not hardcode user-facing strings; route all copy through `Strings.*`.",
               :id :std/swift,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "240",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (240): Swift and SwiftUI style and idioms"}
        #:rule{:title
               "Validation at boundaries — schemas and validation only at interface/external entry points",
               :agent-behavior
               "When writing code inside a component:\n1. Do NOT add `(when (nil? x) ...)` or schema checks on internal data.\n2. If you feel the urge to validate internal data, ask: is this arriving from outside the component? If no, delete the check.\n3. If arriving from outside (via `interface.clj`), add the validation there — and remove it from the internals.\n4. The schema lives in `schema.clj` or `spec.clj` — not scattered across `core.clj` with `when-let` guards.",
               :enforcement
               {:action :warn,
                :message
                "Standard: Validation at boundaries — schemas and validation only at interface/external entry points"},
               :applies-to
               {:phases #{:release :review :verify :plan :implement}},
               :severity :major,
               :knowledge-content
               "# Validation at Boundaries (ALWAYS)\n\n**Validate once, at the edge. Trust everything inside.**\n\n## The rule\n\nSchemas and input validation belong at **two places only**:\n\n1. **Interface boundaries** — the `interface.clj` of a Polylith component. Data entering a component is validated here. Inside the component, trust the data.\n2. **External entry points** — HTTP handlers, CLI argument parsing, event ingestion, file reads. Anything arriving from outside the JVM process.\n\nEverywhere else — inside components, between internal namespaces — **no validation**. Data flowing through internal calls is already valid by construction.\n\n## Why\n\nValidation is expensive to read and to run. Redundant internal validation:\n- Adds noise that obscures business logic\n- Creates false confidence (\"everything is validated\") while actually missing real boundaries\n- Leads to defensive programming anti-patterns (`when (some? x) ...` everywhere)\n- Diverges: schemas at the top and bottom of a call chain often disagree silently\n\nIf internal data is invalid, the bug is in the caller — not in the callee's missing check. Fix the caller. Don't hide it with a check.\n\n## Interface boundary pattern\n\n```clojure\n;; components/task/src/ai/miniforge/task/interface.clj\n;------------------------------------------------------------------------------ Layer 0\n;; Public API — validate here, then forward\n\n(defn create-task\n  \"Create a new task. Validates input at the component boundary.\"\n  [task-data]\n  (let [valid (m/validate TaskSchema task-data)]\n    (when-not valid\n      (throw (ex-info \"Invalid task-data\" {:data task-data\n                                           :errors (m/explain TaskSchema task-data)})))\n    (core/create-task-impl task-data)))  ; inside core: no re-validation\n```\n\n```clojure\n;; components/task/src/ai/miniforge/task/core.clj\n;------------------------------------------------------------------------------ Layer 0\n;; Internal implementation — no validation\n\n(defn create-task-impl\n  \"Create a task record. Input is pre-validated by interface.\"\n  [task-data]\n  (-> task-data\n      (assoc :task/id (random-uuid))\n      (assoc :task/created-at (Instant/now))))\n```\n\n## External boundary pattern\n\n```clojure\n;; bases/api/src/ai/miniforge/api/handlers.clj\n;------------------------------------------------------------------------------ Layer 0\n;; HTTP boundary — validate incoming JSON here\n\n(defn handle-create-task [req]\n  (let [body (parse-body req)]\n    (if-let [errors (validate-create-task-request body)]\n      (bad-request errors)\n      (task/create-task body))))  ; component interface takes it from here\n```\n\n## What does NOT need validation\n\n- Function calls between files within the same component\n- Function calls from `core.clj` to other internal namespaces\n- Data threading through a pipeline (`->`, `->>`, `as->`)\n- Return values of pure functions (they can't be invalid by construction)\n\n## Agent behavior\n\nWhen writing code inside a component:\n1. Do NOT add `(when (nil? x) ...)` or schema checks on internal data.\n2. If you feel the urge to validate internal data, ask: is this arriving from outside the component? If no, delete the check.\n3. If arriving from outside (via `interface.clj`), add the validation there — and remove it from the internals.\n4. The schema lives in `schema.clj` or `spec.clj` — not scattered across `core.clj` with `when-let` guards.\n\n## Anti-patterns to reject\n\n- Validating in both `interface.clj` and `core.clj` — pick one (interface)\n- `(when (some? x) (do-thing x))` inside pure functions — caller is responsible\n- Schema validation inside pipeline stages (`->`) — validate before the pipeline\n- HTTP handler calling `valid?` AND the component interface calling `valid?` again\n- Defensive `(get m :key \"default\")` sprinkled through internals — that's validation in disguise",
               :always-inject? true,
               :id :std/validation-boundaries,
               :detection {:type :custom},
               :category "004",
               :description
               "Engineering standard (004): Validation at boundaries — schemas and validation only at interface/external entry points"}],
